We have $\mathbf{P} \begin{pmatrix} 4 & 3 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 3 \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{P}$.
Let $\mathbf{P} = \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix}$, so 
\begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 4 & 3 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 4a-b & 3a \\ 4c-d & 3c \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}
and 
\begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 3 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ 3c & 3d \end{pmatrix}. \end{align*}
Then we get the system of equations \begin{align*} a &= 4a-b \\ b &= 3a \\ c &= 4c-d \\ d &= 3c. \end{align*}
Solving yields $a = b = c = d = 0$. However, $a$, $b$, $c$, and $d$ are all nonzero, so there is no solution.

Therefore, the smallest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d|$ is $\boxed{7}$.
